1. Be3 { The English Attack is one of the more popular variations of the Najdorf in recent years.
White places their dark-squared bishop, which is their good bishop, on e3 to try to take advantage of the weakness created on b6 by the move a6.
Black can try to attack the bishop right away with Ng4, but white will be able to transpose into the mainline with Bg5, and black wastes a tempo.
White's goals are to play f3 to stop the possibility of ng4 or bg4 in the future. f3 also helps with traditional Sicilian attacks with moves like g4 and h4 to attack the kingside.
Black's plan is to play e5 and try to control d5 so white cannot maintain a piece there. } 1... e5 2. Nb3 { White can also move to f3, but b3 is more popular.
Black's goals are to get both bishops to e7 and e6, play b5, nd7 and nb6 to really control the d5 square.
In some cases, the light-squared bishop finds itself on b7 and black has a lot of pressure on the e4 square. } 2... Be6 3. f3 Be7 4. Qd2 { White is planning to play g4 and h4 to create a kingside attack with a pawn storm.
One variation to prevent this is to play h5. Another is to castle and let the white pawns advantage. A third is to continue on the queenside with nd7 and complete development.
All of these variations will be explored in the English Attack course.
Play h5 to continue to the next lesson. } 4... h5 *


