1. Bg5 { Bg5 is the mainline of the Najdorf. White continues developing the queenside pieces. The goal is to create a kingside attack with f4, bring the queen to f3, castle queenside, and begin the pawn storm.
Black's usual plans are to play the e pawn to e6 rather than e5. This helps to defend the knight without the fear of doubling your own pawns, while also controlling the d5 square so the white knight doesn't occupy it. } 1... e6 2. f4 { White gets on with the king side attack and plays f4 to allow the queen to come to f3 where it has an x-ray on f7. White is also immediately threatening to win the knight with e4 since the knight is pinned.
Black does not always castle in this variation as there is too much pressure on the kingside.
There are multiple variations for black at this point. The plans revolve around defending the f6 knight with a piece (be7 or nbd7), creating counter play with the poisoned pawn variation (Qb6), and complicating the game with b5 (the Polugaevsky).
We will explore the latter two in the next two lessons. For now, we can continue with the second most popular move, Be7. } 2... Be7 3. Qf3 { White continues to develop in traditional fashion and is ready to castle on the queenside.
The most common replies are Qc7, h6, and Nbd7.
Qc7 activates the queen and indirectly controls the e5 square to prevent white from playing e5.
Black's goals are to bring the knight to d7, play b5, and Bb7.
Since white's goals are to play g4 and h4, if black can get a bishop on b7 with the queen on c7 protecting it, then white has a more challenging time playing e5 since the queen and rook would be under attack from the light-squared bishop. } 3... Qc7 4. O-O-O { Black can continue the main plans with Nbd7. } 4... Nbd7 5. g4 { Black can continue with the plan and play b5 to bring the bishop to c7. White does not have a discover attack on the rook on a8 and knight on f6 thanks to the queen protecting the b7 square for the bishop. } 5... b5 6. Bxf6 { The bishop capturing is one variation, but the main goals of the opening have been achieved for both sides. The game will be determined based on who achieves the full fruition of their plans first.
White will continue the pawn storm while black will plan to attack the kingside with moves like b4 and putting pressure on the c2 pawn. } *


