{ The poisoned pawn variation arises out of the mainline of Bg5.

Black still continues with e6 to prevent the knight from coming in to d5. }
1... e6 2. f4 { In the poisoned pawn variation, black moves the queen out of the pin and creates counter play by attacking the weak b2 pawn with Qb6. } 2... Qb6 3. Qd2 { White's most common answer is to give up the weak b2 pawn for more activity. This variation is called the poisoned pawn because black gains a pawn, but white's activity is often enough compensation because the queen is away from the defense of black's kingside where it needs to be.
The black queen can also find itself trapped if it is not careful.
Let's venture into the lions den with Qxb2. } 3... Qxb2 4. Rb1 { The rook is protected by the knight and the queen move earlier to d2 now shows as the queen protects the knight. The black queen is forced to a3. } 4... Qa3 5. e5 { Here's one example of how white can keep black passive. e5 forces black to make a decision. Black scores better when replying with h6 and attacking the bishop, but let's see what happens if black captures the pawn. } 5... dxe5 6. fxe5 { Black can still transpose into the previously mentioned h6 to attack the bishop, but let's play the more common Nfd7. } 6... Nfd7 7. Ne4 { Notice how much activity white has and how passive black's pieces are. Most of black's pieces are not developed because black moved their queen 3 times.
Black can continue to play greedily by now capturing the pawn on a2, going up 2 pawns. Top level play suggests that white wins more than half of the time and black wins about 12% of games in this case.
In general, you want to develop your pieces rather than moving your queen around the board. White is two moves away from casting and there is a tremendous pressure on the kingside. } *


