1. Bg5 e6 2. f4 { The Polugaevsky variation is a complicated variation in which black seemingly gives up their knight by allowing the e4 pin by playing b5.
The move baits white into playing e4 and if white is not careful, they can find themselves in a bind early. } 2... b5 3. e5 { Black captures the pawn. } 3... dxe5 4. fxe5 { Now black plays Qc7, moving out of the way of the pin, but allowing the knight to be captured.
Thanks to the early incoordination of the white pieces and the exposed king, black is able to keep the game even tacticvally. } 4... Qc7 5. exf6 { The queen can now check the king and pick up the bishop to even the game. } 5... Qe5+ 6. Be2 Qxg5 7. O-O { Now the toughest move to find if you're unsure what to do. Ra7.
Black has trouble developing the bishop or the knight and the best thing to do this early is to bring the rook to d7 where it pins the knight to the queen.
Only then can black play Bb7 since it doesn't block the rook in the corner.
Additionally, after white captures on g7, there is a lot of pressure on f7 and the rook on the 7th rank helps prevent any strikes against it. } 7... Ra7 8. Qd3 Rd7 9. Ne4 { Finally, the queen belongs on e5 where the knight on d4 is exposed.
This is a tricky variation, but definitely a fun one to try out. } 9... Qe5 *


