1. h3 { The Adams attack is a slightly obscure move that accomplishes a lot of the same goals of white.
White plans to create a kingside pawn storm at some point and play g4 and f4. g4 is also a great positional move as it helps fight for the d5 square by forcing the knight on f6 away.
In more other variations, white plays f3 then g4 and h4. However, f4 is a more central pawn thrust and has more purposes than h4 does. White doesn't waste a tempo in this variation by playing f3 then f4, which also weakens the g4 square.
Since white can continue to play f4 without fear of giving up control of the g4 square, this move makes sense even if it is slower.
Let's play e5 to continue. } 1... e5 2. Nde2 { White's goals are to play g4 early, move the bishop to g2, and the knight to g3 where it can control or move into f5.
All of these moves help to control the d5 square as white can also play g5 and kick the knight away.
Black's main plan is to stop this early by playing h5 and control the g4 square.
Let's play h5 to move on to the next lesson. } 2... h5 *


